            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Daly City to Filipino immigrants, Mateo Alani\u2019s childhood was a blend of American suburbia and the rich traditions of his parents\u2019 homeland. His father, a mechanic, and his mother, a nurse, instilled in him a profound work ethic and a deep appreciation for the communal joy of family meals, where lumpia and pancit were staples of every celebration. This early exposure to the power of food to bring people together sparked a lifelong passion.\n\nWhile his parents hoped he\u2019d pursue a stable career like medicine or law, Mateo was drawn to the choreographed chaos of restaurant life. He started as a dishwasher during summers, working his way through a Hospitality Management degree at San Francisco State University. After a decade of managing high-volume restaurants, he saw a ceiling. To break through, he pursued an MBA at night, trading sleep for spreadsheets. The degree was his key, unlocking the door from the restaurant floor to the executive suite.\n\nNow the Director of Operations for a prestigious restaurant group, Mateo is a master of logistics and refinement. His biggest turning point was a professional one: overseeing the launch of a Michelin-starred flagship restaurant, a venture so stressful and demanding it contributed to the amicable end of his twenty-year marriage. They had simply grown into different people, their paths diverging under the immense pressure of his career.\n\nToday, Mateo lives a life of disciplined elegance in an immaculate Hayes Valley condo. His day begins before sunrise with a 3.5-mile MUNI ride downtown. He spends his hours in meetings, analyzing profit and loss statements, and solving the complex human and logistical puzzles behind serving thousands of patrons a week. He is respected, if not intimately known, by his colleagues. His social life revolves around the industry\u2014dinners with chefs, drinks with sommeliers.\n\nAt 50, Mateo feels a quiet yearning for something more personal. He has achieved the success his parents dreamed of, but his own dream is now taking shape: to open a small, intimate bistro of his own. A place that marries the innovative techniques he\u2019s mastered with the Filipino flavors of his youth, a true culinary tribute to his San Francisco story."
